  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights during a journey can seem daunting, but it's a straightforward process if you follow these steps. Here\u2019s a guide to help you navigate your layover in Paris en route to Prague:\n\n### Before You Travel\n\n1. **Check Your Itinerary**: Make sure you know the exact details of your flights, including:\n   - Departure and arrival times for both flights.\n   - Terminal information for both your arrival in Paris and your departure to Prague.\n   - The minimum connection time required, which can usually be found on your airline's website or your booking confirmation.\n\n2. **Understand Baggage Handling**: If your flights are booked on a single ticket, your baggage will typically be checked through to your final destination. If you booked separate tickets, you might need to collect your baggage in Paris and check it in again for your Prague flight.\n\n3. **Visa Requirements**: Check if you need a visa for France, even if it's just for a layover.\n\n### At Paris Airport\n\n1. **Arrival in Paris**:\n   - After disembarking, follow signs for \"Connecting Flights\" or \"Transfers.\"\n   - If you need to collect your baggage, head to the baggage claim area.\n\n2. **Security and Immigration**:\n   - Depending on the airport layout, you might need to go through security again. Follow signs and instructions from airport staff.\n   - If you're coming from outside the Schengen Area and your connecting flight is within the Schengen Area, you'll need to go through passport control.\n\n3. **Navigating the Airport**:\n   - Paris has two main airports: Charles de Gaulle (CDG) and Orly (ORY). Ensure you know which one you\u2019re using for both your arrival and departure.\n   - Use airport maps or apps to find your way. CDG, for example, is quite large and has multiple terminals.\n\n4. **Checking In for Your Prague Flight**:\n   - If you need to check in again, proceed to the appropriate airline counter.\n   - If you've already checked in online, you might still need to drop off baggage or get your boarding pass printed.\n\n5. **Boarding Your Flight to Prague**:\n   - Arrive at the gate with plenty of time to spare. Boarding usually starts about 30-45 minutes before departure.\n\n### Tips for a Smooth Connection\n\n- **Time Management**: Aim to be at the gate for your Prague flight at least 30 minutes before boarding starts.\n- **Ask for Help**: Don\u2019t hesitate to ask airport staff for assistance if you\u2019re unsure about anything.\n- **Stay Updated**: Check flight information screens for any updates or gate changes.\n- **Plan for Delays**: If your first flight is delayed, inform the airline staff as soon as possible. They can help rebook you if necessary.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to successfully navigate your layover in Paris and continue on to Prague without issues. Safe travels!",
